      Web3, also known as Web 3.0, is a vision for the next generation of the internet. It's based on blockchain technology, decentralization, and token-based economics. 
      What's Web3 about?
      • Decentralization: Web3 aims to give users more control over their data and how it's used. 
      • Blockchain: Web3 uses blockchain technology to record transactions in a decentralized ledger. 
      • Smart contracts: Web3 uses smart contracts, which are software programs that automatically execute when certain conditions are met. 
      • Cryptocurrencies: Web3 uses cryptocurrencies to facilitate peer-to-peer transactions. 
      **What are the benefits of Web3? 
      • Increased privacy: Web3 gives users more control over their data and who can access it.
      • Improved customer service: Web3's transparency can improve customer service by giving both parties access to transaction records.
      • Better supply chain management: Web3 can help businesses monitor their supply chains by breaking down data silos.
      Who introduced the term Web3? 
      • Gavin Wood, co-founder of Ethereum, introduced the term in 2014.
      How can I learn more about Web3? 
      • You can check out resources from Coursera, Simplilearn.com, and McKinsey & Company.

        What does Web3 mean?
        Web3 is an umbrella term for technologies like blockchain that decentralize data ownership and control on the internet. Most internet applications are controlled by centralized entities that determine how they save and use end-user data.

        What is an example of a Web3?
        One example of Web3 technology is non-fungible tokens (NFTs) that can represent ownership of digital assets such as artwork, music, and collectibles. NFTs provide a way for creators to monetize their digital creations and for collectors to own unique, verifiable digital assets.

        What is Web3 vs blockchain?
        Blockchain enables transparent recording transactions, whereas Web3 allows interactions between users and applications in a more decentralised and democratic way. Web3 enables the use and development of dApps, while Blockchain is more connected with cryptocurrency, such as Bitcoin.
